\chapter{Light-induced resonant nuclear excitation}
\label{chap:bloch}


%------------------------------------------------------------------------------------%

The study of the resonant laser-nucleus interaction is considered to be strongly promoted by the development of the fourth generation x-ray sources like super-intense XFEL. Although the XFEL-photon energies allow to employ solid-state target scenarios, the available frequency range is still limited ($\lesssim 25$~keV) such that the list of suitable nuclear transitions is short. In particular, low-lying electric dipole ($\mathcal{E}1$) transitions which are mainly used in atomic quantum optics, are hard to find in the nuclear domain. However, in Ref.~\cite{Adriana2008.PRC} it has been shown that in nuclear systems electric dipole-forbidden transition can have matrix elements of comparable magnitude with those of electric dipole-allowed transitions. Especially, $\mathcal{M}1$ and $\mathcal{E}2$ transitions are mostly found in the energy range where resonant photons are accessible by today's x-ray sources.

In order to describe the direct, resonant light-nucleus interaction we use the density matrix formalism well known from quantum optics \cite{ScullyZubairy}. Within this formalism the dynamics of the nuclear system is determined in dependence of the considered interaction Hamiltonian including all relaxation channels. Here, a semiclassical approach is applied where the nuclear quantum system interacts with a classical radiation field. Furthermore, the theoretical approach is introduced on the example of a two-level system since the x-ray field is nearly resonant with a single nuclear transition.

This Chapter mainly follows the approach presented in Refs.~\cite{Adriana2008.JoMO} and \cite{Adriana2008.PRC}, and references therein. The general framework of the density matrix formalism applied to quantum optical systems can also be found in standard textbooks like for instance Ref.~\cite{ScullyZubairy}. In particular Sec.~\ref{sec:QD} introducing the basic equations describing the quantum dynamics of the nuclear system follows Ref.~\cite{ScullyZubairy}. Afterwards the calculation of the interaction matrix elements is presented in Sec.~\ref{sec:rad-ampl}. Therein, the multipole expansion of the electromagnetic field is applied which allows to go beyond electric dipole transitions. The final Sec.~\ref{sec:collective} follows the work published in Ref.~\cite{Junker2012.NJP} where collective effects and their influence on the laser-induced nuclear excitation are studied. Atomic units $\hbar=m_{\rm{e}}=e=4\pi\varepsilon_0=1$ are used throughout this Chapter.


%------------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\section{Basic quantum dynamics}
\label{sec:QD}

The natural and most convenient way to describe the direct laser-nucleus interaction is via the well-established density matrix formalism. In this formalism the time evolution of the density matrix $\rho$ is determined by the master equation \cite{ScullyZubairy}
%
\begin{equation}
\i \frac{\partial}{\partial t} \rho=[H_0+H_{\rm{I}},\rho]+\mathcal{L}\rho\ .
\label{eq:master}
\end{equation}
%
The so-called Lindblad operator $\mathcal{L}$ includes decoherent relaxation processes of the system like spontaneous decay or dephasing of the laser field.

Since we are interested here only in the interaction between the nuclear degrees of freedom and the electromagnetic field, the total Hamiltonian can be split into an unperturbed part $H_0$
%describing the nuclear dynamics in absence of the laser field
and a part $H_{\rm{I}}$ describing the laser-nucleus interaction which can be written as
%
\begin{equation}
H_{I}=-\frac{1}{c}\int \d^3r \,  \bm{j}_{\rm{n}}(\bm{r})\cdot \bm{A}(\bm{r},t)\ .
\label{H_int}
\end{equation}
%
Here, $c$ stands for the speed of light and $\bm{j}_{\rm{n}}$ represents the nuclear current density. The vector potential of the electromagnetic field denoted by $\bm{A}$ is described classically. In the Coulomb gauge it is given by \cite{Adriana2008.PRC}
%
\begin{equation}
\bm{A}(\bm{r},t)=\frac{c}{\omega_k}E_k \e^{-\i\omega_k t} \e^{-\i\bm{k}\cdot\bm{r}} \bm{e}^*_{\bm{k}\sigma}+{\rm c.c.}\ ,
\label{eq:vector-pot}
\end{equation}
%
where $E_k$ represents the electric field amplitude, $\bm{k}$, $\omega_k$ and $\sigma$ are the photonic wave vector, frequency and transversal polarization, respectively, and $\bm{r}_{\rm{n}}$ denotes the nuclear spatial coordinates. Here, we exemplarily consider polarization vectors $\bm{e}^*_{\bm{k}\sigma}$ with $\sigma=\pm1$ which refers to circularly polarized light. The generalization to arbitrary polarizations is straightforward.


\begin{figure}
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.4\linewidth]{pics/2-level_scheme.pdf}
\caption{Nuclear two-level system resonantly driven by a laser field. The ground state $G$ is considered to be stable, whereas the width of the excited state is composed of two parts: the decay back to the ground state $\Gamma^{E \to G}$ and a loss channel $\Gamma^E_{\rm{loss}}$ which removes nuclear state population from the system.}
\label{fig:2-level}
\end{figure}


For the considered scenario of resonant or near-resonant photoexcitation it is adequate to describe the nucleus as a two-level quantum system consisting of the states \ket{G} and \ket{E} as shown in Fig.~\ref{fig:2-level}. Each of these states is composed of a set of hyperfine levels characterized by their total angular momentum $I_l$ and projection $M_l=-I_l, \dots,I_l$, with $l \in \{g,e\}$ referring to the states \ket{G} and \ket{E}, respectively. The unperturbed Hamiltonian of the considered two-level system can be represented by
%
\begin{equation}
H_{0}= \omega_g \ketm{G}\bram{G} + \omega_e \ketm{E}\bram{E}\ .
\label{H_0}
\end{equation}
%
Furthermore, the laser is assumed to be nearly resonant to the nuclear transition energy $\omega_0 =  \omega_e - \omega_g$ in order to drive the nuclear population from the ground to the excited level. The ground state \ket{G} is thereby assumed to be stable, whereas the excited level \ket{E} has a natural transition width $\Gamma_0$ which can be written as
%
\begin{equation}
\Gamma_0 = \Gamma^{E \to G} + \sum_{F \neq G} \Gamma^{E \to F} = \Gamma^{E \to G} + \Gamma^{E}_{\rm{loss}}\ ,
\label{eq:Gamma_0}
\end{equation}
%
where the contribution $\Gamma^{E}_{\rm{loss}}$ integrates possible loss channels removing occupation from the considered two-level system for instance by decay paths not reaching \ket{G}. This contribution is in particular important for the cases where the initial state \ket{G} does not coincide with the ground state of the nucleus.

The main purpose of this Section is to derive the optical Bloch equations which fully determine the dynamics of the considered system. Therefore, the master equation (\ref{eq:master}) is projected onto the states \ket{G} and \ket{E} which results in a system of differential equations for the density matrix elements $\rho_{ab}$ with $a,b \in \{g,e\}$,
%
\begin{align}
\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\rho_{\rm{gg}}(M_{\rm{g}}) &= -2\, {\mathrm{Im}}\left(\sum_{M_{\rm{e}}}\rho_{\rm{ge}}(M_{\rm{g}},M_{\rm{e}})\e^{\i\omega_kt}\langle I_{\rm{e}} M_{\rm{e}}|H_{\rm{I}}|I_{\rm{g}} M_{\rm{g}}\rangle\right)
\nonumber \\
&\qquad
+\sum_{M_{\rm{e}}}\gamma^{E \to G}(M_{\rm{g}},M_{\rm{e}})\rho_{\rm{ee}}(M_{\rm{e}})\ ,
\nonumber \allowdisplaybreaks[2] \\
%%
\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\rho_{\rm{ge}}(M_{\rm{g}},M_{\rm{e}}) &= -\i\Delta\rho_{\rm{ge}}(M_{\rm{g}},M_{\rm{e}})
+\i \left (\rho_{\rm{gg}}(M_{\rm{g}})-\rho_{\rm{ee}}(M_{\rm{e}}) \right )\e^{-\i\omega_kt} 
\langle I_{\rm{g}} M_{\rm{g}}|H_{\rm{I}}|I_{\rm{e}} M_{\rm{e}} \rangle
\nonumber \\
&\qquad
-\frac{\gamma^{E \to G}(M_{\rm{g}},M_{\rm{e}})}{2}\rho_{\rm{ge}}(M_{\rm{g}},M_{\rm{e}})-\gamma_{\rm{dec}}\rho_{\rm{ge}}(M_{\rm{g}},M_{\rm{e}})\ ,
\nonumber \allowdisplaybreaks[2]\\
%%
\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\rho_{\rm{ee}}(M_{\rm{e}}) &= 2\, {\mathrm{Im}}\left(\sum_{M_{\rm{g}}}\rho_{\rm{ge}}(M_{\rm{g}},M_{\rm{e}})\e^{\i\omega_kt}\langle I_{\rm{e}} M_{\rm{e}}|H_{\rm{I}}|I_{\rm{g}} M_{\rm{g}} \rangle\right)
\nonumber \\ \label{eq:bloch}
&\qquad
-\rho_{\rm{ee}}(M_{\rm{e}})\sum_{M_{\rm{g}}}\gamma^{E \to G}(M_{\rm{g}},M_{\rm{e}})-\gamma_{\rm{loss}}^E(M_{\rm{e}})\rho_{\rm{ee}}(M_{\rm{e}})\ .
\end{align}
%
In the derivation of Eqs.~\eqref{eq:bloch}, a transformation to a rotating frame was applied in order to eliminate the rapidly oscillating terms from the equations of motion. Moreover, the detuning $\Delta$ is defined by the difference of the transition frequency $\omega_0$ and the photon frequency $\omega_k$. The limited coherence time of the laser pulse is described as decay of the nuclear coherences $\rho_{\rm{ge}}$ with decay rate $\gamma_{\rm{dec}}$. The partial decay rates $\gamma^{E \to G}(M_{\rm{g}},M_{\rm{e}})$ of the upper level \ket{E} are given by \cite{Adriana2008.PRC}
%
\begin{equation}
\gamma^{E \to G}(M_{\rm{g}},M_{\rm{e}})=\frac{2I_{\rm{e}}+1}{2L+1}C\big(I_{\rm{g}}\ I_{\rm{e}}\ L;M_{\rm{g}}\ -\!M_{\rm{e}} \ M\big)^2\:\Gamma^{E \to G}\ , 
\end{equation}
where $L$ and $M$ are the multipolarity and projection quantum numbers of the decay photon and $C(j_1\ j_2\ j_3; m_1\ m_2\ m_3)$ stand for the Clebsch-Gordan coefficients. Summing the partial decay rates $\gamma^{E \to G}(M_{\rm{g}},M_{\rm{e}})$ over all possible projections $M_{\rm{g}}$ and $M_{\rm{e}}$ recovers the total rate $\Gamma^{E \to G}$. Similarly, the contribution from the loss channel $\gamma^{E}_{\rm{loss}}(M_{\rm{e}})$ may depend on the projection quantum number $M_{\rm{e}}$. The optical Bloch equations (\ref{eq:bloch}) can be solved numerically once the interaction matrix elements \me{I_{\rm{e}} M_{\rm{e}}}{H_{\rm{I}}}{I_{\rm{g}} M_{\rm{g}}} are known.




%------------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\section{Interaction matrix elements}
\label{sec:rad-ampl}

In atomic physics the electromagnetic field is usually described in terms of plane waves as shown in Eq.~\eqref{eq:vector-pot}. The photons are characterized by their wave vector $\bm{k}$ and the polarization $\sigma$. In nuclear systems, it is often more convenient to use the angular momentum $L$ with projection $M$ and the transition parity to define the photonic states. Therefore, the electromagnetic field is expanded in terms of its electric and magnetic multipoles $\bm{A}_{LM}^{\mathcal{E}}$ and $\bm{A}_{LM}^{\mathcal{M}}$ \cite{Rose},
%
\begin{equation}
\bm{A}(\bm{r},t) = \frac{c}{\omega_k}E_k \e^{-\i\omega_k t} \sum_{LM} \sqrt{2\pi(2L+1)}(-\i)^L \mathcal{D}^L_{M\,-\sigma}(\hat{\bm{k}}) \left( \bm{A}_{LM}^{\mathcal{M}}(\bm{r})+\i\sigma\bm{A}_{LM}^{\mathcal{E}}(\bm{r})\right)\ ,
\label{multipole}
\end{equation} 
%
where $\mathcal{D}^L_{M\,-\sigma}(\hat{\bm{k}})$ represents the Wigner rotation matrix \cite{Edmonds} turning the quantization axis ($z$-axis) into the direction of $\hat{\bm{k}} = \bm{k}/k$. The electric and magnetic multipole fields $\bm{A}_{LM}^{\mathcal{E}}$ and $\bm{A}_{LM}^{\mathcal{M}}$ are eigenfunctions of both $\bm{L}^2$ and $L_z$ and are themselves solutions of the field-free Maxwell equations. According to Ref.~\cite{Rose} they are given by
%
\begin{align}
\bm{A}_{LM}^{\mathcal{M}}(\bm{r})&=j_L(kr)\bm{Y}_{LL}^M(\theta,\varphi)\ ,
\nonumber \\
\bm{A}_{LM}^{\mathcal{E}}(\bm{r})&=\sqrt{\frac{L+1}{2L+1}}j_{L-1}(kr)\bm{Y}_{LL-1}^M(\theta,\varphi)-\sqrt{\frac{L}{2L+1}}j_{L+1}(kr)\bm{Y}_{LL+1}^M(\theta,\varphi)
\nonumber \\
&= -\frac{\i}{k}\nabla\times \left(j_L(kr)\bm{Y}_{LL}^M(\theta,\varphi)\right)\ ,
\label{eq:multipole-fields}
\end{align}
%
where $j_L$ represent the spherical Bessel functions and $\bm{Y}^M_{JL}$ stand for the vector spherical harmonics defined by \cite{Edmonds}
%
\begin{equation}
\bm{Y}^M_{JL}(\theta,\varphi)=\sum_\nu\sum_q C\big(L\ 1\ J;\nu\ q\ M\big)Y_{L\nu}(\theta,\varphi)\bm{\varepsilon}_q\ .
\label{vsh}
\end{equation}
%
Here, $Y_{L\nu}$ represent the spherical harmonics \cite{Edmonds} and $\bm{\varepsilon}_q$ ($q=0,\pm1$) stand for the spherical unit vectors which can be expressed in terms of the Cartesian unit vectors as follows
\begin{align}
\bm{\varepsilon}_0 &= \bm{e}_z\ , 
\nonumber \\ 
\label{eq:NFS_n+-1}
\bm{\varepsilon}_{\pm1} &= \mp \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \left( \bm{e}_x \pm \i\bm{e}_y \right)\ .
\end{align}
%
The vector spherical harmonics are irreducible tensors of rank $J$ with components $M=-J,\dots,J$. Thereby, $J$ is subject to $L-1 \le J \le L+1$ due to the Clebsch-Gordan coefficient $C(L\ 1\ J;\nu\ q\ M)$. 



%------------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\subsection{Magnetic transitions}

First, we consider the case of nuclear transition with magnetic multipolarity. Inserting the magnetic part of Eq.~\eqref{multipole} into Eq.~\eqref{H_int} leads to
%
\begin{equation}
H_{\rm{I}}=-\frac{E_k}{\omega_k} \e^{-\i\omega_kt} \sqrt{2\pi}\sum_{LM}(-\i)^L\sqrt{2L+1} \mathcal{D}^L_{M\,-\sigma}(\hat{k})\int \d^3r\, j_L(kr)\bm{j}_{\rm{n}}(\bm{r})\cdot\bm{Y}^M_{LL}(\theta,\varphi)\ .
\end{equation}
%
%Typically, the interaction is completely determined by taking only a few terms of multipolarity $L$ into account since the summation over $L$ converges rapidly. 
In the following, the photons are assumed to move along the $z$-axis which reduces the Wigner rotation matrix to $\mathcal{D}^L_{M\,-\sigma}(\hat{k}) = \delta_{M,-\sigma}$. The Kronecker delta $\delta_{M,-\sigma}$ is 1 for $M=-\sigma$ and 0 otherwise.

In nuclear physics, it is usually the case that the wavelength of the radiation is much longer than the nuclear dimension, $kR_0 \ll 1$ such that the long-wavelength approximation is applicable. In this case the spherical Bessel function $j_L(kr)$ can be expanded in terms of the small parameter $kr$. Following the procedure presented in Appendix B of Ref.~\cite{RingSchuck} it is possible to connect the interaction Hamiltonian with the magnetic multipole moments $\mathcalboondox{M}_{LM}$ by expanding up to first order,
%
\begin{equation}
H_{\rm{I}} = E_k \e^{-\i\omega_kt}\sqrt{2\pi}\sum_{L}(-\i)^{L+1}\sqrt{\frac{(2L+1)(L+1)}{L}}
\frac{k^{L-1}}{(2L+1)!!} \mathcalboondox{M}_{L\,-\sigma}\ .
\label{H_int_mag}
\end{equation}
%
Here, $!!$ stands for the double factorial giving $n!!= n (n-2)(n-4)\cdots\kappa_n$ with $\kappa_n=1$ for odd $n$ and $\kappa_n=2$ for even $n$. The magnetic multipole moment is defined by \cite{RingSchuck}
%
%\begin{equation}
%\mathcalboondox{M}_{LM}=\frac{1}{c(L+1)}
%\int d^3r \,
%(\bm{r}\times\bm{j}_{\rm{n}}(\bm{r}))\cdot\bm{\nabla}(r^LY_{LM}(\theta,\varphi))\ .
%\end{equation}
%
\begin{equation}
\mathcalboondox{M}_{LM}=-\frac{\i}{c}\sqrt{\frac{L}{L+1}}\int \d^3r \, r^{L}\bm{Y}^{M}_{LL}(\theta,\varphi)\cdot\bm{j}_{\rm{n}}(\bm{r})\ .
\label{eq:M_LM}
\end{equation}
%
According to Eq.~\eqref{H_int_mag}, the calculation of the magnetic interaction matrix elements reduces to the evaluation of \me{I_{\rm{e}}M_{\rm{e}}}{\mathcalboondox{M}_{LM}}{I_{\rm{g}}M_{\rm{g}}}. Since $\mathcalboondox{M}_{LM}$ is a spherical tensor it is possible to apply the Wigner-Eckart theorem \cite{Edmonds} which isolates the dependence on the projection quantum numbers from the dynamics of the system,
%
\begin{equation}
\langle I_{\rm{e}} M_{\rm{e}}|\mathcalboondox{M}_{LM}|I_{\rm{g}} M_{\rm{g}}\rangle=\frac{(-1)^{I_{\rm{g}}-M_{\rm{g}}}}{\sqrt{2L+1}}C\big(I_{\rm{e}}\ I_{\rm{g}}\ L;M_{\rm{e}}\ -\!M_{\rm{g}}\ M\big) \langle I_{\rm{e}}\|\mathcalboondox{M}_{L}\|I_{\rm{g}}\rangle \ .
\label{eq:me-B_mag-0}
\end{equation}
%
After utilizing the Wigner-Eckart theorem the angular dependence of the matrix element is now only included in the factor containing the Clebsch-Gordan coefficient $C(I_{\rm{e}}\ I_{\rm{g}}\ L;M_{\rm{e}}\ -\!M_{\rm{g}}\ M)$. The radial dependence has been separated into the reduced matrix element $\langle I_{\rm{e}}\|\mathcalboondox{M}_{L}\|I_{\rm{g}}\rangle$ which is independent of any projection quantum numbers. The latter can be related to the so-called reduced transition probability $\mathcal{B}$ \cite{RingSchuck},
%
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{B} (\mathcal{M}L,I_{\rm{g}}\to  I_{\rm{e}})=\frac{1}{2I_{\rm{g}}+1}\big|\langle I_{\rm{e}}\|\mathcalboondox{M}_{L}\|I_{\rm{g}}\rangle \big|^2\ .
\label{eq:B_mag}
\end{equation}
%
Inserting this definition into Eq.~\eqref{eq:me-B_mag-0} leads to
%
\begin{equation}
\langle I_{\rm{e}} M_{\rm{e}}|\mathcalboondox{M}_{LM}|I_{\rm{g}} M_{\rm{g}}\rangle= (-1)^{I_{\rm{g}}-M_{\rm{g}}} \sqrt{\frac{2I_{\rm{g}}+1}{2L+1}}C\big(I_{\rm{e}}\ I_{\rm{g}}\ L;M_{\rm{e}}\ -\!M_{\rm{g}}\ M\big)
\sqrt{\mathcal{B}(\mathcal{M}L,I_{\rm{g}} \to I_{\rm{e}})}\ .
\label{eq:me-B_mag}
\end{equation}
%
%Since experimental values are available for the reduced transition probabilities $\mathcal{B}$, we are not reliant on any nuclear model. 
Instead of constructing nuclear wave functions which are typically strongly model dependent, measured data of the reduced transition probabilities is used for the evaluation of the nuclear transition amplitudes. For a specific multipolarity $L$ we obtain the following interaction matrix element
%
\begin{align}
\langle I_{\rm{e}} M_{\rm{e}}|H_{\rm{I}}|I_{\rm{g}} M_{\rm{g}}\rangle &\propto E_k \e^{-\i\omega_kt}
C\big(I_{\rm{e}}\ I_{\rm{g}}\ L;M_{\rm{e}}\ -\!M_{\rm{g}}\ -\!\sigma\big)
\nonumber \\
&\qquad 
\times 
\sqrt{2\pi} 
\sqrt{\frac{L+1}{L}}  \frac{k^{L-1}}{(2L+1)!!} \sqrt{2I_{\rm{g}}+1}
\sqrt{\mathcal{B}({\mathcal{M}}L,I_{\rm{g}}\to I_{\rm{e}}) }\ .
\end{align}
%



%------------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\subsection{Electric transitions}

In the same manner as for magnetic transitions, the interaction Hamiltonian for electric transitions can be expressed in terms of the electric multipole moments $\mathcalboondox{Q}_{LM}$ as follows
%
\begin{equation}
H_{\rm{I}} = E_k \e^{-\i\omega_kt}\sqrt{2\pi}\sum_{L}(-\i)^{L}\sqrt{\frac{(2L+1)(L+1)}{L}}
\frac{\sigma k^{L-1}}{(2L+1)!!} \mathcalboondox{Q}_{L\,-\sigma}\ .
\end{equation}
%
The multipole moment $\mathcalboondox{Q}_{LM}$ is defined by \cite{RingSchuck}
%
\begin{equation}
\mathcalboondox{Q}_{LM}=\int \d^3r\, r^{L} Y_{LM}(\theta,\varphi)\rho_{\rm{n}}(\bm{r})\ ,
\label{eq:Q_LM}
\end{equation}
%
where $\rho_{\rm{n}}$ represents the nuclear charge density. The current density $\bm{j}_{\rm{n}}$ and charge density $\rho_{\rm{n}}$ are connected via the standard continuity equation \cite{BlattWeisskopf}.

In order to express the matrix element $\langle I_{\rm{e}}M_{\rm{e}}|\mathcalboondox{Q}_{LM}|I_{\rm{g}}M_{\rm{g}}\rangle$ in terms of the reduced transition probabilities, the Wigner-Eckart theorem is again utilized resulting in
%
\begin{equation}
\langle I_{\rm{e}}M_{\rm{e}}|\mathcalboondox{Q}_{LM}|I_{\rm{g}}M_{\rm{g}}\rangle = (-1)^{I_{\rm{g}}-M_{\rm{g}}} \sqrt{\frac{2I_{\rm{g}}+1}{2L+1}}C\big(I_{\rm{e}}\ I_{\rm{g}}\ L;M_{\rm{e}}\ -\!M_{\rm{g}}\ M\big)
\sqrt{\mathcal{B}(\mathcal{E}L,I_{\rm{g}} \to I_{\rm{e}})}
\label{eq:me-B_el}
\end{equation}
%
with
%
\be
\mathcal{B} (\mathcal{E}L,I_{\rm{g}}\to  I_{\rm{e}})=\frac{1}{2I_{\rm{g}}+1}\big|\langle I_{\rm{e}}\|\mathcalboondox{Q}_{L}\|I_{\rm{g}}\rangle \big|^2\ .
\label{eq:B_el}
\ee
%
Using Eq.~\eqref{eq:me-B_el} we obtain the following expression for the interaction matrix elements of electric multipolarity $L$
%
\begin{align}
\langle I_{\rm{e}} M_{\rm{e}}|H_{\rm{I}}|I_{\rm{g}} M_{\rm{g}}\rangle &\propto E_k \e^{-\i\omega_kt}
C\big(I_{\rm{e}}\ I_{\rm{g}}\ L;M_{\rm{e}}\ -\!M_{\rm{g}}\ -\!\sigma\big) 
\nonumber \\
&\qquad \times 
\sqrt{2\pi}\sqrt{\frac{L+1}{L}}
\frac{k^{L-1}}{(2L+1)!!}\sqrt{2I_{\rm{g}}+1}
\sqrt{\mathcal{B}({\mathcal{E}}L,I_{\rm{g}}\to I_{\rm{e}}) }\ .
\end{align}
%





%------------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\section{The collective nuclear decay rate}
\label{sec:collective}

The nuclear transition width $\Gamma_0$ introduced in Eq.~\eqref{eq:Gamma_0} is usually composed of two parts: (i) the radiative decay $A_{\rm{r}}$ where the nuclear excitation energy is released in form of a photon, and (ii) internal conversion (IC) which accelerates a bound electron into the continuum due to the nuclear de-excitation. The radiative decay rate $A_{\rm{r}}$ can be again expressed in terms of the reduced transition probabilities analogously to the previous Section. For a given multipolarity $L$, $A_{\rm{r}}$ is determined by \cite{RingSchuck}
%
\begin{equation}
A_{\rm{r}}^{E \to G} = \frac{8\pi (L+1)}{L[(2L+1)!!]^2} \left(\frac{E_{\rm{n}}}{c}\right)^{2L+1} \mathcal{B} (\lambda L, I_{\rm{e}} \to I_{\rm{g}})  \ ,
\label{eq:A_r}
\end{equation}
%
where the parameter $\lambda$ determines whether the transition type is electric ($\lambda=\mathcal{E}$) or magnetic ($\lambda=\mathcal{M}$) and $E_{\rm{n}} = \omega_0$ represents the nuclear transition energy. Moreover, using the principle of detailed balance the transition probabilities corresponding to either down or up conversion can be related via \cite{Adriana2008.PRC}
%
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{B} (\lambda L, I_{\rm{e}} \to I_{\rm{g}}) = \frac{2I_{\rm{g}}+1}{2I_{\rm{e}}+1}  \mathcal{B} (\lambda L, I_{\rm{g}} \to I_{\rm{e}}) \ .
\end{equation}
%
Typically, $\Gamma_0$ is in the range of $10^{-5}$ to $10^{-10}$~eV in the case of nuclear transitions. The large discrepancy between the nuclear width $\Gamma_0$ and the XFEL bandwidths currently in the order of several eV is one of the main limiting factors for the direct laser-nucleus interaction. However, if solid-state targets are considered there can be a third decay channel, the collective or coherent decay, strongly enhancing the nuclear transition width and hence the laser-induced nuclear excitation. This collective decay relies on the fact that in solid-state targets with M\"{o}ssbauer nuclei photons can be absorbed and re-emitted recoillessly. The photon momentum is then rather transferred to the whole crystal lattice than to a single nucleus. The probability of recoilless scattering is described by the Lamb-M\"{o}ssbauer factor $f_{\rm{LM}}$ which in the Debye-model is given by \cite{Barb}
%
\begin{equation}
f_{\rm{LM}} = \exp \left[ -\frac{2E_{\rm{R}}}{k_{\rm{B}} \theta_{\rm{D}}} \left( 1+4\frac{T^2}{\theta_{\rm{D}}^{2}} \int_{0}^{\theta_{\rm{D}}/T} \frac{x\, \d x}{\e^x-1} \right) \right] \ .
\label{eq:LambMoessbauerFactor}
\end{equation}
%
In this expression $k_{\rm{B}}$ stands for the Boltzmann constant, $\theta_{\rm{D}}$ is the material-specific Debye temperature and $E_{\rm{R}}$ denotes the recoil energy depending on $E_{\rm{n}}$. We will always assume the sample to be at room temperature $T=300$~K.

Due to the recoilless scattering it is impossible to distinguish which nucleus has been excited such that a collective excitation also known as nuclear exciton is created \cite{NFS-bible}. Any process like IC, nuclear recoil or spin-flip leaving a trace of nuclear excitation immediately destroys the collective nature at the nucleus where it took place. The origin of the excitonic state is explained in much more detail in Chap.~\ref{chap:NFS}. Here, it is at first only important to know that the collective excitation predominantly decays by emitting a photon into the forward direction with an enhanced decay rate $\Gamma$ \cite{NFS-bible}. For instance, by considering a laser pulse $\delta$-like in time and $\Gamma^E_{\rm{loss}}=0$, the time dependence of the scattered intensity immediately after the interaction with the laser pulse can be approximated by \cite{NFS-bible,Shvydko1999.PRB}
%
\begin{equation}
I(t) \propto \e^{-(\xi+1)\Gamma_0 t}\ ,
\end{equation}
%
where $\xi=\frac{1}{4}\sigma_{\rm{R}} n_0 L$ stands for the dimensionless thickness parameter with $n_0$ denoting the number density of nuclei in a sample of length $L$. The radiative nuclear resonance cross section $\sigma_{\rm{R}}$ is given by
%
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{\rm{R}} = 2\pi \frac{2I_{\rm{e}}+1}{2I_{\rm{g}}+1} \left(\frac{c}{E_{\rm{n}}}\right)^2 \frac{1}{1+\alpha_{\rm{ic}}} f_{\rm{LM}}\ .
\end{equation}
%
Here, $\alpha_{\rm{ic}}$ represents the so-called IC coefficient which gives the ratio of the internal conversion and radiative decay rate. Including the collective decay channel the following formula for the total transition width is obtained
%
\begin{equation}
\Gamma \simeq (\xi+1) \Gamma_0 \ .
\label{eq:gamma-coll}
\end{equation}
%
This enhancement is of course only valid as long as it is possible to build up the excitonic state. According to Ref.~\cite{Junker2012.NJP}, there are two length scales limiting the extension of the collective excitation: (i) the photoabsorption length $1/\mu$ describing incoherent scattering and absorption from electrons, and (ii) the focal length of the laser $L_{\rm{foc}}$ over which a resonant photon can be shared by the nuclear sample. The smaller one of these two always dictates the upper limit of $\xi$. In the case of ${}^{57}$Fe, for instance, the photoabsorption length lies around 22~$\mu$m for photons resonant to the nuclear transition from the ground to the first excited state ($\sim 14.4$~keV) \cite{Junker2012.NJP}. The focal length $L_{\rm{foc}}$ is determined by the focal diameter $d_{\rm{foc}}$ and the laser wavelength $\lambda$ via $L_{\rm{foc}}=\frac{2\pi}{\lambda} (d_{\rm{foc}}/2)^2$ which gives twice the Rayleigh length. For a photon energy of $14.4$~keV and moderate laser focusing of $d_{\rm{foc}}\sim100$~nm, $L_{\rm{foc}}$ is always larger than $1/\mu$ leading to a total transition width for the first excited state maximally enhanced by a factor of up to $\xi \sim 87$ \cite{Junker2012.NJP}.


